## Decision 2 — Q1: message-body certification scope (high-assurance / evidence)

**Design (CC).** Full message-body hashing in one update call is infeasible/unbounded. So
`get_state_bytes()` builds its preimage from a **bounded heap projection + a direct-chat counterparts
summary + a tombstone sentinel** — the message **bodies are not in the certified preimage**. Physical body
purge is **deferred GC** (reusing `delete_direct_chat`'s mechanism). Synchrony is met because the sentinel
/ heap projection flip within the same update call, so the post-tombstone hash changes immediately,
independent of the deferred purge.

**What this certifies — and what it does not.**
- Certifies: heap PII cleared + tombstone sentinel set (the state transition).
- Does **not** certify: physical absence of message bodies. At finalization the bodies are still in stable
  memory; final physical erasure comes via the **P3 uninstall** (wipes all stable memory), *after* the
  receipt is generated/exported — i.e. outside the receipt's certification.

**Why it needs a ruling.** Consistent with our standing position — *proof of state transition within a
boundary, not proof of data absence* — **but only if the receipt copy says so**. The P4 / RTS copy must
not imply message bodies are provably deleted at receipt time; it must state: tombstone applied + scheduled
purge, with physical erasure completing on account uninstall. Ties to O2's direct-messages disclosure
(ERASE + DISCLOSE counterpart residual).

**Asked of G:** sign off the certification scope for P1; ratify the P4/RTS copy constraint above. (The
counterparts-summary preimage detail to be verified in the diff review; it is a hash input, not exposed in
the receipt.)

